ing the imposition of Communist rule, arguing that their works reveal a new, "minor" mode of national identity based on the model of the translator. The "minor" emphasizes intercultural exchange, adaptation, and ironic distance in the ways a nation thinks of itself. Drawing on theorists as diverse as Benedict Anderson, Gilles Deleuze, Felix Guattari, and Françoise Lionnet, Sean Cotter proposes that this multilingual and multicultural version of the nation is better suited than older models to understanding a globalized world, one in which translation plays an indispensable role. Sean Cotter is associate professor of literature and literary translation at the University of Texas at Dallas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational characteristics, Romanian. 0aRomanian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRomanians. 0aTranslating and interpretingzRomania. 4aEast European Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046855840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580468558423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580468558/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles